<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="11" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
This species is distinctive in the genus in having a single mid-ventral very darkly sclerotized tongue-like process, interpreted as the fused gonopods. It groups with 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Hydroptilidae" genus="Acritoptila" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Acritoptila crinita" order="Trichoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="crinita">Acritoptila crinita</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Hydroptilidae" genus="Acritoptila" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Acritoptila chiasma" order="Trichoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="chiasma">Acritoptila chiasma</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Hydroptilidae" genus="Acritoptila" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Acritoptila csavar" order="Trichoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="csavar">Acritoptila csavar</taxonomicName>
in having filamentous parameres, but particularly with 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Hydroptilidae" genus="Acritoptila" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Acritoptila crinita" order="Trichoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="crinita">Acritoptila crinita</taxonomicName>
in having paired setose processes laterally on tergite X (Figs 11, 12).
</paragraph>
